Other Devices: Includes pun (words with double meanings – can February march, no but april may.), synecdoche (part representing the whole or vice versa -  can we take a head count), metonymy (using one name for another – kiwis lost the match), litotes (negative statements for positive meanings – did you make this dish- not bad.), hyperbole (exaggeration), and euphemism (expressing taboo or embarrassing things indirectly- saying healthy instead of fat)

Discourse markers are additional elements in language that act as connectors or fillers to join ideas, sentences, or phrases
They also signal a speaker's mood, attitude, or intent to shift or end a conversation
markers for expressing opinions ("wow," "honestly"), starting conversations ("to begin with"), and concluding ("all in all," "in a nutshell")

Rhythm: Described as the "flow" of language, English is stress-timed, meaning prominent syllables occur at roughly regular intervals

Pitch: Determined by the frequency of vocal cord vibration, pitch can be high or low. It conveys emotions; for instance, high pitch often signals excitement, while low pitch can indicate shock or dullness
Intonation: This is the "melody" created by changing the pitch of the voice. It can be rising, falling, or flat. Intonation is crucial for distinguishing sentence types (e.g., turning a statement into a question), resolving ambiguity, and expressing sarcasm or surprise
